:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Many members of the general public are completely unaware that certain domestic electrical work requires certification and notification to meet the requirement of Building Regulations and contract work to unqualified people.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Many adopt the attitude that it’s only a little job, nothing important, but would they let an unqualified person loose on their teeth? Even a small job by an untrained/qualified person is potentially dangerous and can lead to devastating or potentially devastating results.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Members of the public are happy to engage an electrician without checking their qualifications, accreditation or that they are members of a competent person scheme. </span></li></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Some members of the public are prepared to carryout DIY electrical works.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The public need to be made aware of the importance of using qualified registered contractors.  The gas industry has strong public awareness about the dangers of not using a registered trades person as this has been heavily promoted in the past. The electrical industry does not have the same strong awareness amongst the public and this needs to be addressed.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The industry should continue to promote Part P to improve awareness amongst consumers and </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">specifiers</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> and to improve enforcement and policing amongst contractors.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">There were no requirements for enforcement prior to the implementation of Part P and although it took some adjustments within our business in its early days, we have been in full support of the regulation as it gives our business even greater credibility and a reputation as a business that delivers the best quality services by highly qualified personnel.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Part P has increased electrical safety standards in dwellings by forcing many previously unregistered contractors to adhere to common industry standards and regulations.</span></li></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The real challenge is rogue traders and </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">DIYers</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> – it is better to promote registered electricians in approved schemes making it easier for members of the public to identify or know where to at least look for a qualified contractor. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The extent to which those carrying out electrical works are adequately trained to meet the requirements of the Building Regulations and the extent to which all those working for a company are brought up to the same level of skills</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Although it is our company that is registered as a Part P compliant organisation through our Qualified Supervisor, all of our staff are regular reviewed to confirm that they understand the regulations and what is required of them. Our employees have all completed 4 year apprenticeships and been encouraged to continue developing and learning throughout their careers. They receive regular ongoing training to ensure that they are fully up-to-date with the wiring regulations and building regulation requirements for our industry.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The extent to which those carrying out electrical works, to which the Building Regulations apply, review or have their work reviewed to ensure that it meets the requirements of the Regulations</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The current system for review to confirm that a company meets the requirements is satisfactory.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Our company is assessed every year to confirm that we continue to comply with Part P regulations when samples of our work is randomly chosen and checked.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">We are very proud of the work we carry out and the systems that we operate within our business and would be happy for our work to be assessed at any time throughout the year not just at the assessment time.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">We were disappointed when the Part P scheme was amended in April.  We would not wish to see this standard of competency diluted any further </span></li></ul><h1 style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></h1><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The effect of competition between accreditation bodies, and the two separate registers of electricians, on the standards of review of domestic electrical work; and competition </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Competition is good as it keeps the existing accreditation bodies working hard in our industry. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">However 2 separate registers for the industry has and will cause confusion as the public will be unsure which scheme to use. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The strong promotion of one register would be of the most benefit to the industry and the general public.  The </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">CertSure</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> scheme - The Electrical Safety Register has 36,000 contractors from the NICEIC and ECA organisations who are collectively responsible for 92% of all notified domestic work and 90% of all commercial electrical jobs. This makes it the largest database of registered electrical contractors for England, Wales and Northern Ireland.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">If all electricians had to be </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">licenced</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> or registered with one organisation it would help weed out those working the in the industry without the appropriate qualifications and experience.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>